column168: CBPAS Sims discovered approximately 200 aluminum phosphate fumigation tablets in luggage from Nigeria.  These tablets release phosphine gas upon exposure to moisture.  According to MSDS, even exposure to moisture in the air can release enough phosphine to affect human health.  SCBPAS Helfers has triple bagged the tablets in ziplock biohazard bags.   The tablets and passenger are referred to baggage for a refuse entry on the substance.  The passenger is also receiving an Ag penalty.  The tablets will be secured in the stamp room since it has an isolated ventilation system.  Items were disposed of by Hazardous Waste vendor on February 5, 2019.
column169: Customers are advised at time of ticket purchase and check-in hazardous items that are prohibited in checked and carry-on baggage.

column168: A driver filled the CO2 tanker truck. He closed the tanker fill valves and was venting the lines when he went to use the bathroom.  When he returned to the truck he entered the truck cab and pulled away before closing the bulk tank valves or disconnecting the hose from the bulk tank.  When the driver pulled away, the  line broke at an elbow joint  between the hose and the bulk tank. CO2 was released from the bulk tank (est. 50,000 lbs).   The release began at approx. 5:25 am and was clear by 7:00 am.  Highway 190 and the local rail line were closed for approximately 25 min.  Approx. 12 homes were evacuated for 1 hour.  Residents were held in a bus provided by the town of Enfield.  The fire department was able to close the valve on the bulk tank.   The tanker had been filled with 40,000 lb of CO2.  The Bulk tank holds 50 tons of CO2.
column169: SOP review and re-training of all drivers that fill the CO2 tanker trailers. Do not allow personnel to leave the fill site until the filling process is complete, including valve closure and  dis-connecting/venting of all fill lines.

column168: At 1424 ET, ERTS was notified by Dave Kopacz of XPO (XAY) regarding a cargo release. column168: On February 8, 2019 at 0157 EST, ERTS was contacted by a truck driver from XPO Logistics Domicile terminal LLR in regards to a spill in Shreveport, LA on an exit ramp off of Interstate 20 leading to Monkhouse Drive. The driver reported that he experienced a roll over resulting in the release of UN1133 to the trailer floor. LA Highway Police was first to the scene and received report #19-00538 at 0140 EST. ERTS then notified the Caddo Parish of the incident but did not receive a report number. ERTS then completed the online LADEQ report and received report #QV0J 7894. ERTS dispatched USES to manage the spill. Once the contractor arrived on site, they unloaded most of the cargo into a relief trailer with a forklift so the original trailer could be moved. At 0953 EST, the contractor followed the trailer back to XPO Logistics terminal LSL to finish cleanup of the trailer. At 1019 EST, the contractor arrived at the terminal and indicated that (2) 5-gallon metal pails of UN1133, 3, PGII (DSB 1516) were damaged and released approximately 9 gallons to the trailer floor. A 55-gallon metal drum waste container was generated containing the damaged metal pails as well as cleanup debris weighing approximately 120 pounds. All waste was left on site in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: At 0244 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics Terminal NAT that they had experienced a release of UN1203, 3, II (Gasoline) at 0230 EST. It was reported that approximately 55-gallons of gasoline had released to the tail of trailer #3112231 and impacted the dock floor below from a 55-gallon metal drum due to being punctured by a forklift while loading. At 0338 EST, ERTS dispatched First Environmental Nationwide to manage the spill. At 0755 EST, the contractor arrived on site and began assessing and cleaning the spill. All impacted absorbents were placed in (2) 55-gallon metal drums and the damaged drum was placed in an 85-gallon metal drum. All waste was left on site and staged at terminal OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column43: Zing® Formula IV Aluminum Pontoon/Boat Cleaner
column168: At 1504 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO terminal XCO regarding a cargo release. It was reported that approximately 1 gallon of UN2922, corrosive liquid, 8, 6.1, PG II (Zing® Formula IV Aluminum Pontoon/Boat Cleaner) from (2) 1-gallon plastic pails had burst to the dock floor due to the cold temperatures at the terminal. ERTS dispatched EMS (OH) to conduct cleanup operations. At 1748 EST the contractor arrived on site and began the assessment and cleanup process. The contractor tested the pH of the product then treated the spill with proper neutralizer. The damaged box, all (4) 1-gallon plastic pails in the box, spent absorbent, neutralizer were all placed inside a 55-gallon poly drum. All waste was staged in terminal OS&D and left for the terminal to manage.

column168: On February 7, 2019 at 0300 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics terminal XGH regarding a release. It was reported that approximately 30 gallons of UN1170 Ethanol, solution, 3, PGIII (Abex 23 S) released from (2) 55-gallon poly drums to the tail of the trailer due to being punctured by a forklift while loading. A total of 9 drums of waste were generated and staged at OS&D and left onsite for the terminal to manage.

column168: At 0130 ET, ERTS received a call from John "Jacob" Viozzi of Penske regarding a cargo tank rolled over and hazardous materials release around Litiz, PA. Penske truck #125802 (trailer # unknown at the time of the call but as a holding place caller gave "F-01")was hauling UN3257 "Elevated Temp Asphalt" when the vehicle rolled over due to poor weather conditions resulting in the release of an estimated 10-20 gallons of material to the soil down an embankment. Clean Harbor, stated that at least half of the trailer product has been transferred to spare tanker. Contractor stated that no diesel fuel has been released and both saddle tanks are intact. Contractor stated that truck and trailer are upright and wrecking company getting it ready to take it away. Contractor will commence cleaning area were approximately 15 gallons have been released and product has solidified. Contractor stated all area affected was clean and generated 3-55 gallon drum of waste.  Contractor staged the waste onsite and will get back with ERTS to coordinate waste pickup and disposal date.

column168: On February 11, 2019 at 0947 EST, Jeff Lewis with MC Tank contacted ERTS regarding a UN1866, Resin Solution, 3, PG II release that occurred at 0937 EST at a customer location, Spectra Composites, 177 Wool Road, Jamestown, SC. It was advised that 20 gallons of product released to the soil only due to a blown hose on trailer CH3594.  HEPACO arrived on onsite and reported that 10 gallons or less of product was released to a 4' x 6' area of the soil and concrete steps. HEPACO has completed cleanup efforts and (2) 55-gallon metal drums have been taken off site for disposal pending approval from MCT Transport.

column168: On February 12, 2019 at 0527 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO terminal UKC regarding a hazardous cargo release. It was reported that due to improper loading from the previous terminal a 55-gallon poly drum of UN3266 Corrosive liquid, basic, inorganic, n.o.s., 8, PGII (Big Bang) sustained a loosened cap while in transit. As a result, it was reported that approximately 6 ounces leaked to the top of the poly drum only not impacting any floors. It was reported that terminal personnel moved the drum to the dock floor. ERTS instructed the caller to wear the proper PPE being chemical resistant gloves and safety goggles and then wipe away the released product with an absorbent pad then remove and re-secure the cap of the drum. The drum was agitated to test for any further leakage. It was advised that there was no further leakage and the task was complete. The drum was then sent on to the consignee. All waste generated being impacted absorbent pads were placed in a 5 gallon plastic pail and was staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: On February 12, 2019 at 1834 EST, ERTS was notified by XPO Logistics terminal ULA in Sante Fe Springs, CA that 8 gallons of UN1263 Paint (flammable), 3, PGII (Caterpillar paint) was released from (2) 5-gallon metal pails and (1) 1-gallon metal pail to the trailer floor due to improper loading by the XSL terminal. The caller reported that due to the strong odor, the trailer was parked in the yard. At 1919 ET, ERTS dispatched Patriot Environmental Services for to conduct cleanup operations. ERTS notified CEMA of the incident and Devin issued control # 19-1003. ERTS also notified Santa Fe Springs Fire-Rescue (CUPA) of the incident but no report number was issued. At 2006 EST, the contractor arrived on site and began the assessment and cleanup process. The contractor reported that (7) 1-gallon paint cans and (2) 5-gallons were not damaged and were placed in (1) 55 gallon steel drum to be sent on. The contractor generated (1) 55-gallon metal drum of damaged pails, impacted absorbents, spent PPE, debris weighing 190 pounds. All waste was staged on site and left for the terminal to manage.

column168: A Veolia employee was loading containers onto a trailer and noticed a 10 gallon cardboard box leaking  liquid.  The box was a lab pack containing 6 x 1 quart bottles and 12 x 206 milliliter bottles of sulfuric  acid solution.  One of the 206 milliliter bottles that was packed into the container was broken, which  cut the inner liner of the cardboard box, causing the spill.  The spill was cleaned up and the entire  leaking container was overpacked in accordance with the hazardous materials regulations.
column169: The employee who packed the container was retrained on the lab packing regulations and reminded that broken inner packaging should never be packed into an outer package that could be punctured or sliced, causing a leak.  The employee was also retrained on the requirements to include cushioning  material and absorbent material in a quantity enough to absorb the entire liquid contents contained in the inner packaging's.  Disciplinary action was taken against the employee.

column168: A Clean Harbors Environmental Services, Inc. driver arrived at the shipper’s location to transport a preloaded roll off bin to a local Clean Harbors Environmental Services Inc. disposal facility in La Porte, TX. During the course of the loading maneuver, the driver and a customer representative discovered a small amount of material coming from the rear door seal of the roll off bin container leaking onto the containment site from which the box was being loaded. Due to previous inclement weather in the area, material inside the roll off bin became saturated. Subsequently, the ground around the roll off bin and the containment device were also saturated, causing the containment device to become fragile and tear as the roll off bin was hoisted atop the roll off truck frame rails. This caused approximately one solid pound of material to make contact with the earth underneath. The driver immediately placed a containment pail under the rear door. The customer representative contacted his dispatcher to request a response crew. Upon notification, the customer’s response crew was summoned, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, removed the released material and placed it into a 55 gallon drum to be disposed of onsite, tightened the rear door which stopped the leak: a containment diaper was secured to the roll off bin as an added measure. The shipment continued on to the disposal destination.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. Upon inspection at the Clean Harbors’ La Porte, TX facility, it was determined the roll off bin was leaking due to the presence of free liquid. In order to prevent a recurrence, the customer facility has been instructed to immediately notify Clean Harbors once a bin has been loaded in order to expedite the transportation and disposal process. The driver has been re-instructed to perform a comprehensive inspection of the container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation.

column168: On February 18, 2019 at 2130 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal UKC regarding a cargo release. The caller reported that due to a mechanical failure of the bottom valve there was a release of UN1993, Flammable Liquid, NOS, (Kerosene Xylenes), 3, PGIII "Unisol Liquid- Red" from (1) 330-gallon metal tote. A contractor was dispatched and arrived onside at 0110 EST. The contractor confirmed approximately 8-ounces released from a semi-open valve on the bottom of the tote to an 8' x 1' area of the trailer floor. The contractor tightened the valve completely then wrapped the handle to prevent the valve from accidentally opening again. The contractor then wiped down the impacted parts of the valve as well as the released material. The released material, absorbents as well as the rags used were all placed inside (1) 5-gallon poly drum.  All waste was staged in OS&D on site for the terminal to manage.

AT APPROXIMATELY 16:00 CST ON 2/2/2019 ENERGY DISPATCH SENT 2 DRIVERS TO RACETRAC #2506 FOWLER TO PUMP-OUT APPROXIMATELY 5300 GALLONS OF DIESEL BECAUSE THE STATE OF FLORIDA TOLD OUR CUSTOMER (RACETRAC) THAT THE PRODUCT WAS OUT OF SPEC. THIS PROCEDURE REQUIRES TO PEOPLE, ONE ON TOP OF THE TRAILER AND ONE ON THE GROUND. OUR TRAILERS HAVE 5 COMPARTMENTS AND WHEN THEY WHERE PUMPING INTO THE 3RD COMPARTMENT THE DRIVER ON TOP OF THE TRAILER HAD LEFT HIS POSITION WHICH REQUIRES HIM TO VISUALLY WATCH THE PRODUCT RISE FROM ON TOP OF THE TRAILER TO ENSURE THAT AN OVERFILL DOES NOT HAPPEN. BECAUSE HE LEFT HIS POSITION HE FAILED TO LET THE DRIVER ON THE GROUND WORKING THE PUMP CONTROLS KNOW THAT THE COMPARTMENT WAS FULL RESULTING IN THE OVER FILL. THE DRIVERS SAW THE DIESEL COMING OUT OVER THE TOP OF THE TRAILER ONTO THE GROUND AND IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE PUMP. THEY BEGAN TO IMMEDIATELY PLACE ABSORBENT PADS OUT TO CAPTURE AS MUCH OF THE PRODUCT AS POSSIBLE. THEY CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THEN REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE SAFETY MANAGER ON DUTY WHO IN TURN CALLED OUT CURA (3RD PARTY VENDOR) TO GO SEND SOMEONE TO THE SITE AS SOON AS POSSIBLE TO CLEAN UP AND ASSES THE MAGNITUDE OF THE SPILL. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED FIRST AND DEPLOYED ABSORBENT PADS AND ABSORBENT BOOMS TO THE IMPACTED AREA. HULL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED ON BEHALF OF ENERGY DISPATCH TO THE SITE THROUGH CURA. HULL ARRIVED ON-SITE AT APPROXIMATELY 18:25 CST. THE SITE EXPERIENCED RAIN DURING THE EVENT AND ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE DEPLOYED INTO THE STORM DRAIN AND RETENTION POND LOCATED ON THE STORE PROPERTY. THE RELEASE WAS APPROXIMATELY 80 GALLONS. THE FLORIDA STATE WARNING POINT (FSWP) WAS VERBALLY NOTIFIED AT APPROXIMATELY 18:25 CST ON THE AFTER HOURS NUMBER. INCIDENT # 2019-655. AT APPROXIMATELY 18:34 CST THE INCIDENT WAS VERBALLY REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER (NRC) AFTER HOURS HOT-LINE. INCIDENT #1236632 WAS ISSUED.
column169: ENERGY DISPATCH CONDUCTED RE-TRAINING FOR BOTH INDIVIDUALS INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT AS WELL AS DOCUMENTATION STATING WHAT THE CAUSE WAS AND WHAT THEY MUST DO TO STOP THIS FROM HAPPENING IN THE FUTURE. WE ALSO SCHEDULED REFRESHER TRAINING FOR ALL OUR TEAMS THAT ARE APPROVED TO CONDUCT PUMP-OUTS THROUGHOUT THE COMPANY.

column168: The drum that reacted was only 1/3 full so there was significant head space. The head space had the potential to generate moisture (condensate) due to temp changes. The styrene would have reacted with the moisture. Once the drum was put on the truck and “agitated” the reaction stared again. At least this is my hypothesis.   The client describes the waste stream as “stabilized.” In our vocabulary that means that the monomer has been inhibited which would prevent the reaction from continuing. The client used the word to mean that the reaction had ended. Nothing had been added (inhibitor) to cease the reaction. Clearly not all of the styrene had reacted.
column169: All of the material has been cleaned up and shipped off for final disposal. I will keep you posted as we conclude the investigation.  Univar will not be accepting that particular waste stream until Quantum has completed its investigation, identifying a root cause and corrective actions to address the non compliance.

column168: During an inspection at a port of entry in Laredo TX, a release of a corrosive liquid was found.  The lid(closures) to the IBC totes were found loose. One lid was cross threaded.  During the shipment the material splashed out of the containers through their lids, since they were not properly secured.  Less than 2 gallons of product was lost. A team was called and they removed all containers from the trailer, cleaning as they went. They tighten the lids and replaced the cross threaded lid with a new lid.  The team reloaded the trailer and secured the contents.
column169: A procedure is in place that requires the cargo to be checked prior to loading and anytime it is trans loaded. This is part of having a secured load.

column168: On February 12, 2019 at 2320, ERTS was contacted by a truck driver from XPO Logistics. He was requesting response to an XPO trailer on it's side in the median of I-275 in Romulus, MI south of the I-275 & I-94 junction near the airport. It was advised by the driver that the trailer does contain mixed freight including hazmat. The driver reported a liquid releasing having a strong odor. Police believed the release to be Organic Peroxide. At 0900 EST, the contractor arrived on site. It was confirmed that the released product was UN3103, Organic peroxide type C, liquid (tert-Butyl peroxybenzoate, 98%), 5.2 "TBPB" and that it was the only hazardous material in the shipment. All cargo was loaded from the damaged trailer into the relief trailer by the contractor with an extended reach forklift. At 1033 EST, the contractor departed site and went to the XPO Logistics terminal in Romulus, MI. After arrival to the terminal, the contractor inventoried the freight and containerized all freight that could not be salvaged. The contractor re-stacked and re-wrapped 2 pallets of undamaged Organic Peroxide jugs. The contractor stated that (8) 1-gallon poly jugs in 2 boxes were damaged releasing no more than 1 gallon of product that they believed was absorbed within the fiberboard boxes. The contractor placed 38 loose 1-gallon poly jugs inside of (2) 55-gallon poly drums that were sent on to the consignee. The contractor generated (2) 55-gallon poly drums of waste. One drum containing the damaged jugs and the other drum containing impacted debris and PPE. All waste was left on site in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: At 1045 EST, ERTS was contacted by personnel at the XPO Logistics terminal located in Jacksonville, FL regarding a cargo release. It was reported that due to a 2-vehicle accident, (1) 550-gallon metal tote of UN1263, Paint Related Material, 3, PGIII "Household Paint" had been damaged and was leaking it's contents onto US1 - County Rd 121. At 1135 EST, ERTS dispatched Hepaco to respond. At 1234 EST, the contractor reported that both lanes of traffic were closed and couldn't get to the site. At 1500 EST, the contractor arrived on site. The contractor stated that the fire department had place AFFF over the spilled paint. It was also reported that the soil had been impacted and needed remediation. Prior to the contractor arriving onsite, the XPO relief trailer was on site. The relief trailer was loaded with the rest of the freight and taken to the XPO Logistics terminal in Jacksonville, FL. At 1743 EST, the contractor reported that the XPO trailer involved in the accident had been removed from the site. Hepaco generated (5) 55-gallon steel drums of waste containing impacted absorbents and debris. At 1845 EST, the contractor departed site with the waste. At 2120 EST, the contractor arrived to the XPO Logistics terminal in Jacksonville, FL to drop off the waste drums. The waste was staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

column168: At 2130 hrs. on 2-21-2019, the WLE Brewster Yard Car Inspector noticed and odor coming from  car PROX 36770 and notified the Yardmaster who then called me, John Vergis, Environmental Officer for the WLE.  When I came out to inspect, I found that there was vapor leaking from the valve plug on  the vapor valve.  I checked to see if the valve was tight and it was not.  I tightened the valve handle  and the leak stopped.  The plug was not even close to hand tight so I properly tightened it. I checked the liquid valve plugs and they were not hand tight either so I tightened them also.  I  removed Seal #4979273 from the protective housing lid and the installed new seal #971751 and then  released the car for service.    NARRI: 5(4+5)x2=47                                            Cause Codes:379 The waybill does not show the proper shipper.  It shows Centennial Energy who is the gas broker. column168: On February 27, 2019 at 1304 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal NRO regarding a cargo release. It was reported that approximately 0.5 gallon of UN1263, Paint, 3, PGII "BE-NA0007 Flint Primer" released from (1) 55-gallon metal drum while unloading. It was reported that the drum fell over while unloading causing nail sized holes in it. The caller requested a contractor be dispatched because they did not have a big enough over pack to put the damaged drum in. The terminal personnel plugged the punctured drum to prevent any further release. At 1629 EST, the contractor arrived on site and stated that there was a small line of paint from the punctured drum. Terminal personnel had cleaned the spill with speedy dry and placed the impacted absorbents inside (1) 10-gallon metal drum. The contractor over packed the damaged 55-gallon drum inside (1) 85-gallon metal drum. All waste was left on site and staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

On February 27, 2019 at 1046 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal XAY regarding a cargo release. It was reported there was a release of UN3082, Environmental hazardous subs liquid n.o.s. (contains sodium nitrit) 9, PGIII "Corrosion Inhibitor TR81160" from (1) 270-gallon poly tote due to what appeared to be a faulty seam at the bottom. The terminal requested a contractor be dispatched to do a tote transfer. At 1215 EST, the contractor arrived on site. It was confirmed that approximately 1 teaspoon of product released to the tray on the metal cage located on the dock. The contractor completed a tote transfer on site. After the transfer was done, the contractor cut the damaged tote up and placed it inside (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The metal cage was placed in XPO recycle. The waste drum generated was left on site in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

AWB 027-8000-9296 1PC 12LBS OF BIOLOGICAL SUBSTANCE, CATEGORY B TRAVELED BOISEA AS2003/13FEB. AN UNINTENTIONAL RELEASE OF LIQUID CONTENTS OCCURRED JUST BEFORE DELIVERY OF PACKAGE TO COURIER. THE LIQUID WAS CLEAR AND ODORLESS. AGENTS HAD NOT NOTICED THE PACKAGE LEAKING AND MOVED THE ITEM ON A PLATFORM TRUCK APPROXIMATELY 20 METERS. APPROXIMATELY 300ML OF LIQUID WAS RELEASED ALONG THE PATH OF THE PLATFORM TRUCK FOR A DURATION OF APPROXIMATELY 1 MINUTE. THE AREA WHERE THE SPILL OCCURRED WAS STANCHIONED OFF FROM FOOT TRAFFIC AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS DISPATCHED TO ASSIST WITH HAZARD IDENTIFICATION AND SPILL CLEANUP PROCEDURES. A DISPATCH AGENT FOR THE SHIPPER WAS ABLE TO BE REACHED. THIS PERSON ADVISED THAT THE SHIPMENT WAS AN "ANIMAL BIOLOGICAL SUBSTANCE" AND THAT IS WAS NOT HAZARDOUS TO HUMANS. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT MADE AN ASSESSMENT AND ALSO ADVISED THAT THE SUBSTANCE WOULD BE SAFE TO CLEAN UP WITH STANDARD CLEANING PRODUCTS. NEITHER EXPOSURE NOR INJURY TO PERSONNEL OCCURRED. THE PACKAGE WAS RELEASED TO THE CONSIGNEE'S COURIER AFTER BEING PLACED IN TWO GARBAGE BAGS. NO OPERATIONS IMPACTED AND THE AREA WAS RETURNED NORMAL OPERATION SOME 40 MINUTES AFTER INITIAL RELEASE.

column168: Tank Car TILX 290456 reported leaking product from top of tank car. Inspection found release from the Manway with all Swingbolts tool tight. Upon opening the Air Valve to relieve pressure, liquid product was present indicating the car was shell full. Response Personnel off loaded a portion of tank car in order to give head space in the car to work on Manway Gasket and stop release. Approximately 55 gallons of product was removed from the car into two drums and staged for disposal. The Inlet Gasket appeared to be worn and  pinched where the Nozzle seats in the Manway Lid. Response Personnel placed with a new gasket Nozzle Gasket. Car was secured and released back into transportation.

column168: On February 26, 2019 at 0820 EST, ERTS was contacted by XPO Logistics terminal NGV regarding a cargo release. It was reported that there was a release of UN 2735, Amines, Liquid, Corrosive, N.O.S. (cyclohexylamine; dimethylaminopropylamine (DMAPA)), 8, PGII " Steamate Pas 4010" from (1) 130-gallon metal IBC to the dock floor. It was reported that terminal personnel set the tote a little too hard on the dock while unloading causing the valve on the tote to go loose and the product to drip. The caller stated that he had tightened the valve and secured it so no more product was releasing. The terminal did request ERTS to dispatch a contractor to conduct cleanup operations. The contractor arrived on site and confirmed that approximately 1-gallon of product had released to a 5' x 5' area of the concrete dock from the loose valve. The contractor confirmed the valve was tightened and secured to continue transport. The impacted concrete was neutralized with citric acid then solidified with pads. The impacted debris was placed inside (1) 55-gallon poly drum. The waste was left on site and staged in OS&D for the terminal to manage.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, A VEHICLE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN A FIRE/EXPLOSION IN THE MOTOR VEHICLE. THE CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE CONSISTED OF 5 COMPARTMENTS, WHICH CONTAINED DIESEL FUEL AND GASOLINE. APPROXIMATELY 1,500 GALLONS OF DIESEL FUEL WERE WITHIN ONE COMPARTMENT, WHICH WAS INVOLVED IN THE FIRE/EXPLOSION. THE MAJORITY OF FUEL WAS BURNT UP IN THE FIRE, HOWEVER, SOME FREE PRODUCT DID RELEASE TO ASPHALT ROADWAY AND ADJACENT SOIL DITCH. THE SOIL DITCH CONTAINED FREE STANDING WATER, WHICH MIGRATED TO A NEARBY STORM DRAIN AND CULVERT BENEATH ROADWAY. THE GEORGIA DOT AND EPA RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. DOT ASSISTED IN CONTAINMENT WITH THE APPLICATION OF ABSORBENTS TO THE DITCH. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL  WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM CLEANUP. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENT UTILIZED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER FREE STANDING WATER AND PRODUCT FROM WITHIN DITCH, AND PROCEEDED TO FLUSH THE IMPACTED STORM DRAIN. ABSORBENT BOOM WAS LEFT WITHIN DITCH, AND AT OUTFALL TO THE STORM DRAIN, TO CATCH RESIDUAL PRODUCT. THERE WAS NO IMPACT OR THREAT TO ENTER STATE WATERS. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL RETURNED TO THE SITE TO EXCAVATE IMPACTED SOILS, AND RESTORE SITE TO PREEXISTING CONDITION. CONFIRMATION SAMPLES WERE PULLED TO CONFIRM ALL CONTAMINATION HAD BEEN RECOVERED, AND DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES RESORTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.

column168: Our driver picked up two totes and as proceeding out of the facility, noticed a fog coming from the trailer. The driver was instructed to immediately pull back into the dock to receive assistance from the customer to identify the problem. The investigation revealed that the driver failed to adequately secure his pallet jack. The pallet jack rolled into the tote causing damage to the tote and material to be released inside the trailer. Univar personnel responded to the release and diluted the released material. They also secured the damaged tote in order to prevent further release of product.
column169: Had the driver adequately secured the pallet jack for transit, this incident would not have occurred. The driver was disciplined according to company policy. This incident may be used as a discussion topic in future driver meetings to illustrate the importance of proper blocking and bracing practices.

column168: The Univar Tractor Tanker was traveling at the intersection of HWY 176 and FM 181 when he was hit on the side (back rear of the tanker) and lost control.  The full contents of the tanker approximately 5,074 gallons of Methyldiethanolamine (MDEA) was released on the road and shoulder area.  The material was cleaned up over time.  The driver of the tractor trailer that hit the Univar tanker also lost control and died.  As a precaution the Univar employee was airlifted to a hospital in Odessa, Texas as his body took the impact of the hit.  Univar then called in CURA for remediation and clean up efforts that lasted into the next day. NRC was called by the Regional Regulatory Manager at 10:35 am the same day.  The NRC Report given is: 1236852.  The TX SERC was called, but they did not take a report or give a report number.  TCEQ Region 7 was onsite during the investigation and clean up.  Calls from EPA Region 6 were also taken and reports sent.   30 day closure reports have been sent to TX Dept of public safety, TCEQ Region 7, EPA Region 6, Andrews County Emergency Management and the state police.  If a report is necessary for the DOT, please contact Gail Backus.

column168: UNIT 1 WAS NORTHBOUND ON US 183, APPROX .4 MILES NORTH OF COUNTY ROAD (EW 6). THE DRIVER OF UNIT 1 STATED HE MET AN ONCOMING VEHICLE AND ONCE THE VEHICLE PASSED BY HIM THE FRONT PASSENGER SIDE TIRES DROPPED OFF THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY. THE DRIVER DID NOT KNOW WHY IT HAPPENED. I BELIEVE THE DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED BY SOMETHING INSIDE OR OUTSIDE OF UNIT 1. UNIT 1 DEPARTED THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT AND TRAVELED APPROX 59 FT BEFORE OVERTURNING 1/2 TIMES. THE A01 WAS APPROX .4 MILES NORTH OF THE CENTER OF EW 6 AND APPROX 29 FT EAST OF THE CENTER OF US 183. THE AOR FOR UNIT 1 WAS APPROX 40 FT NORTH OF THE A01. THE TRUCK CAME TO REST ON ALL FOUR WHEELS FACING NORTH AND THE TRAILER CAME TO REST ON ITS TOP. THERE WERE NO VISIBLE SKID MARKS PRIOR TO IMPACT.

Original comments:  The sort manager brought the package to QA.  The outer package appeared wet, but there was no leakage coming from the package.  The package does have orientation arrows, and when opened, the 2 bottles of product and a brochure were sitting in crunched paper and the liquid from the larger bottle (32oz, which has a cracked base.  Almost all of the liquid from the bottle had emptied into the inner package.  The crunched paper seemed to absorb the liquid and keep it from leaking entirely but was not enough of a cushion/buffer between the items and outer package.  New Comments:

Original comments:  I was called to route 183 for a possible damaged Hazmat. I identified the package as a flammable liquid UN1133 Hazmat Class 3 Packaging Group II. The name of the substance was identified as Formica 268R LOW VOC Spray Grade Contact Adhesive. A red liquid adhesive was observed protruding from bottom of metal pail. I identified a dent and a puncture at bottom of the metal pail, so it is believed to have been dropped. All safety precautions were taken when handling and transporting Hazmat from Work area to Hazmat cage. Gloves were utilized and metal pail was placed in red hazmat bin. Hazmat held in Hazmat cage awaiting Disposition.  New Comments:

Original comments:  As package was being unloaded it was noted that corner of box was wet.  Pkg was segregated and moved to QA.  Upon inspection, QA determined this was an undeclared Hazmat and moved it to the Hazmat cage.  QA noted that battery appeared to be wet at top corner of plastic casing.  Packaging did not fail but was wet.  Package was placed in tote bin until further instructions were received at which time item was transferred to a salvage drum and sealed.  New Comments:
Original comments:  The package was the found by a package handler on the van lines  New Comments:

Original comments:  While a package handler was unloading the trailer, they noticed a wet/leaking hazmat and informed their manager. The manager got on the radio and informed QA of the situation they had in their unload.  QA grabbed a red tote, lined with a hazmat bag and grabbed loose absorb. They rushed over to the area to investigate the situation. Upon arrival, they noticed the package in question was Corrosive and placed it in the tote.  QA cleaned up the area with the loose absorb. Once the area was cleaned, they brought the package back to QA placing it in the hazmat processing cage.  New Comments:

column168: Driver hooked unloading hose up to rear end of the trailer to being unloading Ferrous Chloride when he noticed the hose and gasket were both iced up from the ice storm. He then began to tighten the four bolt flange down and began unloading with no leaks. After about twenty five minutes the ice melted from around hose end and gasket which created a gap between the gasket and the flange. The product was sprayed due to product temperature. The rear valve was then shut off by the driver. About 10 gallons of ferrous chloride was released into containment.

column168: Original comments:  Damaged upon arrival to station. After further inspection by QA, it was determined that one of the plastic jugs foil seal was broken and its cap was loose allowing the liquid to leak out. The liquid spilled over the other jugs in the box and soaked through side of package. It is suggested that shipper tighten all caps and use adequate packing materials when shipping future packages containing such materials. It is also suggested that package handlers follow directional arrows and use more caution when moving hazmat packages. Duration of release was less than 30 minutes.  PRODUCT: Immunocal by StatLab - 1 gallon plastic jugs  New Comments: It is suggested that shipper tighten all caps and use adequate packing materialswhen shipping future packages containing such materials. It is also suggested that package handlers follow directional arrows and use more caution when movinghazmat packages.

column168: Original comments:  QA was notified about a ORM-D labeled package with a strong smell emanating from it. Package was placed in a black tote and brought to QA for inspection. When the package was opened it contained a 5 gallon drum on Paint with a UN # 1263 and Flammable Liquid 3 stickers. The drum had a very small amount of dried white paint coming from the pull out spout in the top on its lid. The spout/valve seemed to have been slightly jarred from its original position. The drum was dented in several places and it is suspected that one these impacts may have jarred the valve. No packing material was around the drum inside of its cardboard box. Because the paint was dried when discovered it is believed that the damage likely occurred during transit.  New Comments:

BOTTLE NO LONGER SEALED PROPERLY. CAP WAS RE TIGHTENED BUT BOTTLE STILL LEAKS IF NOT KEPT UPRIGHT.  New Comments:

column168: On 2/26/2019 two FRA inspectors were doing an inspection of the NS rail yard in Enola, PA. While watching train movements they noticed AEX 16561 a covered hopper rail car moving in the yard with material piled on top of car. The FRA inspectors noticed the car was placard UN1486. 5.1, they then went to the yardmaster for waybill information which showed car as an empty NON HAZ. NS then tracked down shipper to verify if this car should be a placarded last contained rail car or if waybill information was incorrect. It was determined Waybill info was incorrect and car should have a hazmat waybill. An NS approved contractor was notified to clean off the top of the car and verify was indeed empty which it was.  The material on the car was not the result of a release during transit but a car loading/unloading issue. Shipper contacted NS billing department to input correct billing for the car prior to movement. An estimated 150lbs of potassium nitrate was removed from the top of the car.

column168: While loading a box onto the truck at a customer site (Forbes Hospital) with a pallet jack, the forks of  the pallet jack sliced the drum.  The truck was already loaded with drums from a previous customer (PPG) and the Veolia employee was trying to get the pallet jack and the box to fit inside the truck.  The Veolia employee immediately put spill pads down on the floor of the trailer and laid the drum on its side,  slice side up to stop the leak.  The leaking drum was then overpacked and reloaded onto the trailer.
column169: Following the incident, both the Veolia on-site supervisor and the EHS Manager spoke to the employee about being aware of his surroundings and tools.  The employee was recently hired by Veolia.  Veolia used this as a coaching moment to teach the employee about on-site awareness and potential work place hazards.  Veolia also reviewed the incident and talked about ways to avoid similar incidents in the  future.  The employee was also working in a very tight/restricted area due to the truck being loaded with material from their previous stop.  The tight space and employee's experience level were  contributing factors to the incident. The pallet jack was inspected following the incident.  The pallet jack did not have a sharp edge or visible damage that would have lead to the cut on the container.  The  pallet jack must have hit the container in an abnormal or "perfect" way causing the small cut on the  drum.

column169: KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL CONTINUE TO TRAIN AND ENFORCE SAFE LOADING/UNLOADING POLICIES AND PROCEDURES.

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC PERSONNEL WERE TRANSFERRING GASOLINE FROM ONE TANK TRAILER INTO A SECOND TANK TRAILER. THE NECESSITY TO TRANSFER THE GASOLINE WAS DUE TO A MECHANICAL ISSUE WITH ONE OF THE TRACTORS. IN THE COURSE OF THE TRANSFER, ONE OF THE COMPARTMENTS ON THE TANK TRAILER WAS OVERFILLED AND APPROXIMATELY 100 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WAS RELEASED. THE SPILL IMPACTED THE ASPHALT PARKING SURFACE AND MINIMAL AMOUNT MAY HAVE IMPACTED A NEARBY STORM DRAIN.  KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC PERSONNEL IMMEDIATELY EMPLOYED ABSORBENT PADS AND GRANULAR MATERIAL TO REMEDIATE THE SPILL. ONCE COMPLETED, THE ABSORBENTS WERE COLLECTED AND ARE AWAITING PROPER DISPOSAL BY SAFETY KLEEN. THE STORM DRAIN WAS INSPECTED AND IT WAS DETERMINED THERE WAS NO RESIDUAL IMPACTS. REPRESENTATIVES FROM THE BALTIMORE FIRE DEPARTMENT. COAST GUARD AND MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF THE ENVIRONMENTAL WERE ON SITE MONITORING THE REMEDIATION ACTIVITIES.
column169: IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE, KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL TAKE THE FOLLOWING PRECAUTIONS. FIRST, A DRIVER THAT HAS BEEN CERTIFIED USING A PUMP WILL BE PRESENT DURING THE TRANSFER. SECOND, A MINIMUM OF TWO EMPLOYEES WILL BE INVOLVED IN THE TRANSFER PROCESS TO ENSURE THAT AN OVER-FILL DOES NOT OCCUR. IN ADDITION, KENAN TRANSPORT, LLC WILL MAKE SURE THAT THE TRUCK/TRAILER ARE APPROPRIATELY GROUNDED DURING TRANSFER ACTIVITIES.

column168: Driver was parked taking a break while in transit to destination. While parked driver noticed a leak coming from inside the van trailer. Upon inspection of the load, he determined that a tote container was leaking inside the trailer. The plastic totes were double stacked on the trailer and the weight from the top tote partially crushed the bottom tote causing it to bulge. This created a hole in the container which caused the leak. The local fire department responded initially to asses the situation and an emergency response crew was engaged to report to the scene. The response team was able to repair the hole in the tote container and clean up the spilled product inside the trailer. The load was delivered as intended. The trailer was decontaminated and the parking lot was cleaned.

column168: Driver picked up a loaded bulk metal container at shipper. While in transit approximately 20 miles from the shipper, the driver heard a "pop" and looked in the mirror and observed product leaking from the front outlet of the container where a cap should be to cover the outlet. Driver stopped immediately and reported that the front cap had come off of the container during transportation and resulted in a small spill of approximately 10 gallons. The cap was not secured properly before leaving the shipper causing it to come off during transit. An emergency response crew responded to the scene and replaced the cap on the container and performed the necessary spill clean up along with removal and disposal.

column168: The cause of the incident was operator error. The driver was attempting to drop and was unable to connect the vapor recovery hose when,instead of following proper policies and procedures, the driver attempted to reposition the truck with the hose still connected to the truck and UST. As he repositioned the vehicle he ripped the hose causing the release. Driver followed proper spill response procedures by damming the spill with absorbent to prevent it from spreading further. Driver alerted our 24/7 Dispatch team of the release who coordinated with the incident commander to have NRC Environmental Services dispatched out to the site, alert local authorities, and complete notification to the National Response Center.
column169: The involved driver was terminated due to the severity of the incident and blatant disregard for company policy and proper procedures. In order to prevent recurrence, other drivers went through refresher training to remind them of proper loading/ unloading procedures and company policy regarding safe operation of a CMV. This incident was also discussed in each of our site safety committees to further develop strategies to prevent re-occurrence. A training refresher program and open discussion huddles are great tools to decrease the frequency of re-occurrence.

column168: Employees were transporting transformer for disposal in a transformer bag after draining the PCB oil out. Employee put absorbents into the transformer to catch any residual oil, however failed to put absorbents in the transformer bag to catch any oil that may not be caught by the absorbents in the transformer. Upon arrival to the disposal site, the employees discovered the leaking transformer bag. Employees put on the proper PPE, and cleaned up the spill in the back of the box truck using absorbents. Absorbents, and soiled transformer bag were were disposed of properly.
column169: The Employees were retrained on the proper way to prepare the transformer for shipping.

column168: DRIVER WAS APPROACHING THE DELIVERY LOCATION. A COUPLE OF MILES BEFORE THE DELIVERY LOCATION, A DRIVER IN A CAR TRIED TO PASS THE TRUCK, GOT IN FRONT OF THE TRUCK, AND PUSHED THE BRAKES SUDDENLY. TO AVOID COLLISION, COMPANY DRIVER HAD TO PUT THE BRAKE AND WE ASSUME THIS IS WHEN THE LOAD SHIFTED, DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE DELIVERY, AND INSPECTED THE TRUCK AND THE TRAILER AND HE NOTICED A SPILL FROM THE TRAILER. DUE TO THE FACT THAT THE DRIVER WAS NOT ALLOWED TO BREAK THE SEAL TO SEE WHAT WAS GOING ON WITH THE LOAD, HE CALLED THE EMERGENCY NUMBER AT CHEMTREC AND INFORMED THE COMPANY AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT. THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED, BROKE THE SEAL TO MAKE SURE THERE IS NO FIRE DANGER AND THAN THE CLEAN-UP TEAM ARRIVED WITHIN 1, 5 HOURS AND HANDLED THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND THE CLEAN-UP. THERE WERE 37 POLY DRUMS (55 GALLON) AND A HANDFUL OF 5-GALLON PAILS ON BOARD, ONLY 2 OF IT WERE PUNCTURED AND SPILLING. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM ARIZONA'S ADEQ (DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY) WAS ON SITE. HE STATED THAT THE AMOUNT RELEASED FROM THE TRAILER IS NOT A REPORTABLE QUANTITY PER THEIR CRITERIA.
column169: NO COMMENTS PROVIDED.

column168: Original comments:  Package consisting of a 5 gal metal pail in a fiberboard overpack was reported as damaged in sort. A very small amount of the contents had leaked out of the box, and a manager quickly placed it in a plastic Hazmat salvage container to prevent a spill. Upon inspection, it was found that the inner package (metal pail) suffered a large dent on the edge near the lid. It appears that this was caused by an impact in handling - possibly by falling off the load side rollers when waiting to be loaded onto trailer. The dent had allowed lacquer to be released, but the overpack was able to contain almost all of it inside. Once inside the salvage container, the contents slowly started flowing through the closure of the box but all released contents were contained by salvage bucket.  Metal pail has been placed in a large salvage drum along with the wet damaged fiberboard overbox. Leaked remains that were caught by plastic container was placed in a second salvage drum. Both salvage drums are in Hazmat Cage awaiting further instructions.  New Comments:

column168: FRA Hazmat Inspector (Randy Boyington) found the UTLX 679964 to have product on the top and sides of the car.  Mr. Boyington notified BNSF employees who isolated the car in a safe and secure location for inspection and repair.  Hazmat contractors responded and found both protective housing seals intact on the car.  Upon opening the valve housing, it was discovered that the vapor valve was left fully open and the closure plug on the vapor valve was less than tool tight.  Responders secured the valve and cleaned crude oil residue from the car housing and jacket.  No crude oil was observed to have reached the ground.  Volume estimates are based upon observations and visual impacts to the car body.  Once cleaned, the car was released to continue to transportation.
column169: Followed up with shipper to ensure that they review post loading procedures to ensure that valves are closed and secondary closure plugs are in tool tight condition prior to releasing into transportation.(NAR:136)

column42: GASOLINE INCLUDES GASOLINE MIXED WITH ETHYL ALCOHOL, WITH NOT MORE THAN 10% ALCOHOL
column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, A VEHICLE ACCIDENT RESULTED IN A FIRE/EXPLOSION IN THE MOTOR VEHICLE. THE CARGO TANK MOTOR VEHICLE CONSISTED OF 5 COMPARTMENTS, WHICH CONTAINED DIESEL FUEL AND GASOLINE. APPROXIMATELY 972 GALLONS OF GASOLINE WERE WITHIN ONE COMPARTMENT, WHICH WAS INVOLVED IN THE FIRE/EXPLOSION. THE MAJORITY OF GASOLINE WAS BURNT UP IN THE FIRE, HOWEVER, SOME FREE PRODUCT DID RELEASE TO ASPHALT ROADWAY AND ADJACENT SOIL DITCH. THE SOIL DITCH CONTAINED FREE STANDING WATER, WHICH MIGRATED TO A NEARBY STORM DRAIN AND CULVERT BENEATH ROADWAY. THE GEORGIA DOT AND EPA RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE. DOT ASSISTED IN CONTAINMENT WITH THE APPLICATION OF ABSORBENTS TO THE DITCH. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL WAS DISPATCHED TO PERFORM CLEANUP. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL UTILIZED A VACUUM TRUCK TO RECOVER FREE STANDING WATER AND PRODUCT FROM WITHIN DITCH, AND PROCEEDED TO FLUSH THE IMPACTED STORM DRAIN. ABSORBENT BOOM WAS LEFT WITHIN DITCH , AND AT OUTFALL TO THE STORM DRAIN , TO CATCH RESIDUAL PRODUCT. THERE WAS NO IMPACT OR THREAT TO ENTER STATE WATERS. FIRST CALL ENVIRONMENTAL RETURNED TO THE SITE TO EXCAVATE IMPACTED SOILS, AND RESTORE SITE TO PREEXISTING CONDITION. CONFIRMATION SAMPLES WERE PULLED TO CONFIRM ALL CONTAMINATION HAD BEEN RECOVERED, AND DISPOSAL WAS COORDINATED IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.

column168: While preparing to begin product transfer from AP trailer to the customer trailer, the rupture disk on the AP trailer failed as our driver was preparing to open the discharge valve. Our driver was present at the pump cabinet at the time of the rupture disk failure, and was accompanied by 2 customer operators. Based on the fact the pressure safety valve (set at 40 psig) never lifted. It appears the rupture disc (with a burst rating of 65.8 psig) was faulty and burst prematurely.  After the pressure decreased and was under control, our driver was able to safely and successfully transfer product into the customer trailer.
column169: The NA Fleet team began a program in 2012 for atmospheric trailers to convert from a rupture disk/safety valve system to a safety valve only relief system.  About 50% of our fleet has been converted.  It will likely be at least another 5-10 years until we are completely converted. Representative sample from the batch (lot) of discs will be sent to vendor for testing to ensure that entire lot is not defective.

column168: Air Products driver was making an LHY delivery to customer.  Halfway through unloading, driver noticed a small leak developing at the hose connection to the customer tank.  Recognizing the leak, the driver  began the process to shut down the fill.  Driver closed the trycock valve and turned to proceed toward trailer to shut it down as well.  When driver turned toward trailer, he noticed the leak rapidly accelerating  and he made a quick move to get away.  At this same time, the leak ignited.  Driver quickly got back to trailer and shut down the delivery.  With the pump down and the trailer side isolated, the fire slowed significantly, but was still burning, likely due to standing liquid in the hose. After taking a moment to assess the situation, he was able to safely close the top fill valve at the tank, fully isolating the hose on both sides.  Driver promptly notified customer and emergency services for response.  Driver completed a helium purge and disconnected the hose under emergency services supervision. It is estimated that the fire lasted ~15-20 minutes.  During investigation, it was found that the customer tank hose seal was not per design specification.
column169: Check male fitting design bayonet specifications to drawings on all similar tanks in service.  This tank was already corrected following the incident.  Transfer hose and fittings (tank and hose) were sent to manufacturer for further investigation. Reinforce training of all hydrogen drivers on how to recognize possible leak situations.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: ON FEBRUARY 20, 2019, AN EAST PENN NFG CO. DRIVER, OUT OF OUR PITTSBURGH FACILITY, LEFT THE FACILITY AND WAS DRIVING NORTH ON ROUTE 522 ON HIS WAY TO MCVEYTOWN, PA WHEN IT STARTED TO SNOW. THE SNOW CAME DOWN HARD COVERING THE ROAD WITH IN 5 MINUTES OF SNOWING. THE BOX TRUCK THAT OUR DRIVER WAS USING HAD 2 DIFFERENT TREAD TYPES ON ITS REAR WHEELS. ONE TIRE HAD "ALL WEATHER TREAD' AND ONE TIRE HAD "HIGHWAY TREAD".  THE TIRES WERE WITHIN DOT COMPLIANCE. THE TRUCK WAS ALSO CARRYING A LIGHT LOAD. THE DRIVER SLOWED DOWN TO 40 MPH, SLOWER THAN THE 55 MPH SPEED LIMIT BUT STILL LOST CONTROL OF THE TRUCK. THE TRUCK VEERED OFF INTO A DITCH ON THE RIGHT SIDE OF THE ROAD. IT CAME TO A HALT IN THE DITCH AND WAS ON A 45 DEGREE ANGLE. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO GET OUT OF THE TRUCK WITHOUT INJURY. THE SECURED LOAD OF 5 PALLETS DID SHIFT AND CAME UNDONE INSIDE THE TRUCK. THE LEAD ACID BATTERIES WERE ON THEIR SIDE AND UPSIDE DOWN, WITH ACID LEAKING OUT OF THEM. THE SNOW WAS COMING DOWN. THE STATE POLICE, CLINTON COUNTY HAZMAT TEAM, MIFFLIN COUNTY EMA, AND PENN DOT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE. DUE TO THE SNOWY HAZARDOUS CONDITIONS, PENN DOT DIRECTED THAT THE RECOVERY AND CLEAN UP COMPANY COM BACK TOMORROW WHEN CONDITIONS ARE BETTER. THE TOWING/CLEAN UP COMPANY WAS TOLD TO CALL PENN DOT FIRST TO MAKE SURE THAT CONDITIONS WERE SAFE ENOUGH FOR CLEAN UP TOMORROW.  THE FOLLOWING DAY THE TOWING COMPANY AND EMA ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AFTER GETTING PERMISSION FROM PENN DOT. THE BOX TRUCK WAS PULLED OUT OF THE DITCH AND UP-RIGHTED. AGAIN, NO FUEL WAS LOST. IT WAS HARD TO TELL IF ANY ACID LEAKED OUT OF THE BOX TRUCK DUE TO ALL THE SNOW. THE EMA TOLD US THAT ALL WAS GOOD AND THAT NO CLEAN UP WAS NEEDED. THE TRUCK WAS TOWED TO THE TOWING COMPANY YARD.  A FEW DAYS LATER EAST PENN WENT TO THE YARD TO RECOVER THE BATTERIES. THE BATTERIES WERE GONE THROUGH, AT OUR PITTSBURGH, PA FACILITY, ONE BY ONE TO CHECK FOR DAMAGE. THE DAMAGED BATTERIES WERE SHIPPED BACK TO OUR EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO., LYON STATION FACILITY TO OUR SECONDARY LEAD SMELTER FOR RECYCLE/RECOVERY.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS CONSULTED ABOUT GOING TOO FAST FOR THE WEATHER CONDITIONS. THE ACCIDENT WAS SENT TO EAST PENN'S ACCIDENT REVIEW COMMITTEE TO DECIDE IF A CHARGEABLE OR NON-CHARGEABLE INCIDENT. IF THE INCIDENTS DECIDED THAT IT IS CHARGEABLE, THE PROPER DISCIPLINARY ACTIONS WILL BE FOLLOWED.  THE DRIVER'S WERE ALSO GIVEN A TAILGATE, REMINDING THEM ABOUT SAFE DRIVING DURING SNOWY CONDITIONS. THE DRIVER'S WERE ALSO REMINDED THAT IF THEY DO NOT FEEL COMFORTABLE DRIVING IN THE CURRENT WEATHER CONDITIONS, THAT THEY SHOULD NOT GO OUT.  THE TRUCK WAS SENT TO EAST PENN MANUFACTURING CO., LYONS STATION FACILITY TO GO OVER FOR A FULL INSPECTION, INCLUDING THE TIRES . DURING THE INSPECTIONS IT WILL ALSO BE DETERMINED IF THE TRUCK IS A TOTAL LOSS.

column58: Pressure Relief Valve or Device - Non-Reclosing
column168: AT 0140 HOURS ON FEBRUARY 14, 2019, WHILE WORKING IN THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCS) SHREVEPORT, LA RAIL YARD, A CREW NOTICED HAZMAT LOADED TANK CAR UTLX 130768 LEAKING FROM THE TOP OF THE TANK CAR. THE ENVIRONMENTAL & HAZMAT DEPARTMENT MOBILIZED A RAILROAD QUALIFIED EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO INVESTIGATE AND SECURE THE CAR.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONSE CONTRACTOR DISCOVERED THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE (PRD) COMPLETELY OFF (UNBOLTED), LAYING ON TOP OF CAR. THE CONTRACTOR SECURED THE PRD FLANGE ASSEMBLY TO MAKE CAR SAFE SWITCH WITHIN THE YARD. ONCE UTLX 130768 COULD BE MOVED, IT WAS SET OUT, DECONTAMINATED, AND THE REST OF THE CLOSURES CHECKED FOR SECUREMENT.  AFTER NOTIFYING THE SHIPPER, THE SHIPPER WAS ABLE TO PROVIDE PHOTOS OF THE CAR PRIOR TO BEING RELEASED INTO TRANSPORTATION IN A SECURE STATE (ALL EQUIPMENT ON TOP OF CAR WITH SECURITY SEALS IN PLACE - SPECIFICALLY, THE PRESSURE RELIEF DEVICE IN PLACE AND SECURE). AFTER CONSULTING OTHER HAZMAT RESPONDERS, KCS LEARNED THAT THERE HAS BEEN A RASH OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID THEFT FROM RAIL CARS TO PRODUCE METHAMPHETAMINE. BECAUSE OF THIS, IT IS BELIEVED THAT THE PRD WAS REMOVED BY VANDALS IN AN ATTEMPT TO STEAL HYDROCHLORIC ACID FROM THE TANK CAR. THE CAR IS CURRENTLY IN SHREVEPORT WAITING ON AN ONE-TIME MOVEMENT APPROVAL.  FILE NOTE: ITEM 19-THE QUANTITY RELEASED WAS ESTIMATED BASED ON THE BEST INFORMATION AVAILABLE AT THE TIME OF FILING. THIS SHIPMENT WAS OFFERED AS A 'BULK' SHIPMENT , AKA ONE CAR LOAD, THEREFORE THE EXACT AMOUNT OFFERED IN THIS PACKAGE IS NOT KNOWN TO THE CARRIER. THIS CARRIER DOES NOT HAVE ACCESS TO MASS BALANCE DATA WHICH CAN EXACTLY QUANTIFY THIS VALUE.
column169: THE KANSAS CITY SOUTHERN RAILWAY (KCSR) NOTIFIED SHIPPER OF THIS RELEASE. NON ACCIDENTAL RELEASES (NAR) CAN BE DEVASTATING ON SEVERAL DIFFERENT LEVELS. THEY CAN CAUSE PERSONAL INJURY, ENVIRONMENTAL DAMAGE , DISRUPT RAIL YARDS, ADJACENT FACILITIES AND COMMUNITIES, AND SNARL TRAIN OPERATIONS FOR HUNDREDS OF MILES AND BOTH DIRECTIONS. NARS ARE TROUBLESOME TO ALL BECAUSE THEY ARE, BY AND LARGE, PREVENTABLE. FOR NON ACCIDENT RELEASES (A.K.A PACKAGE CLOSURE ISSUES SUCH AS THIS), THE SHIPPER IS REQUESTED TO CONDUCT A ROOT-CAUSE INVESTIGATION TO DETERMINE THE CAUSE(S) OF RELEASE AND TO THEN FACILITATE CORRECTIVE ACTION TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. IT IS REQUESTED THAT THE SHIPPER SHARE THEIR FINDINGS WITH KCS. (PLEASE DIRECT YOUR ROOT CAUSE INVESTIGATION RESULTS AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS TO STEVE MCNEALY, KCS RAILWAY, P.O. BOX 219335, KANSAS CITY, MO 64121. THE SHIPPER CAN REFERENCE HTTP://NAR.AAR.COM FOR HELP UNDERSTANDING AND PREVENTING NARS.

column168: On February 27, 2019, at 0906 ET, ERTS was retained by Schneider Bulk Carriers concerning a hazardous UN3265 "Glycolic Acid 70%" cargo tanker rollover release. It was reported that the Schneider Bulk driver rolled over in a single vehicle accident on the roadside soil ditch with standing water. It was reported that an unknown amount of hazardous UN3265 Glycolic Acid 70% released from 2 washout caps on the tanker. The fire department and EPA representative responded to the site. The fire department pumped out the truck's saddle tank.  A Schneider Bulk relief tanker responded to the site to trans-load the hazardous product with a betts valve. ERTS dispatched USES to conduct remediation activities. At 1445 ET, USES personnel arrived on site and confirmed there was minimal release of product located in the ditch area. The water was not impacted by the material, it was captured in pails and given to USES for disposal. Absorbents booms and pads were utilized to collect released product. USES secured the site with boom and pads to ensure no product could migrate and departed site at 1915 ET.  On February 28, 2019, at 1415 ET, USES personnel returned to the site to continue cleanup activities. An excavator was utilized to scrape the ditch line and collect any residual product that may have been missed during the first response.   On March 14, 2019, at 0830 ET, USES arrived onsite to remove the remaining boom. No further impact remained and no further action was required. USES departed site at 0930 ET. The roll off box generated during cleanup operations is awaiting disposal.

column168: OUR TRUCK WAS CARRYING 7600 GALLONS OF DYED #1 DIESEL AND 1800 GALLONS OF PREMIUM UNLEADED GASOLINE FROM MISSOULA, MONTANA TO GRANGEVILLE, IDAHO. AT MILE MARKER 3 ON IDAHO HIGHWAY 13 OUR DRIVER REPORTS HE WAS CROWDED OFF THE ROAD BY AN ONCOMING UNLOADED LOG TRUCK. (THERE WERE CONFIRMING WITNESSES FROM 2 VEHICLES THAT HAD BEEN FOLLOWING OUR TRUCK). OUR TRUCK AND TRAILER ROLLED OVER ONTO THEIR RIGHT SIDES IN THE BORROW DITCH. THE FRONT COMPARTMENT OF THE TRAILER CRACKED APPROX 14 INCHES AND ABOUT 2270 GALLONS OF DYED #1 DIESEL WERE SPILLED.  A HAZMAT TEAM FROM THE GRANGEVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AT THE SCENE AND BEGAN INITIAL CONTAINMENT. THE TRUCK AND TRAILER WERE DRILLED FROM THE EXPOSED LEFT SIDE AND PUMPED OUT. OUR RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, TETRA TECH, INC WAS DISPATCHED THE SAME DAY TO MANAGE CLEANUP IN COORDINATION WITH THE IDAHO DEQ AND EPA.  SEE ATTACHMENTS.
column169: IN THE CASE, HIGHLY TRAINED AND VERY EXPERIENCED DRIVER - WHO HAD SUCCESSFULLY MANAGED SIMILAR SITUATIONS COUNTLESS TIMES - ENDED UP IN THE DITCH IN AVOIDING AN ONCOMING VEHICLE CROWDING THE CENTER OF THE ROAD ON A SNOWY DAY ON A SHOULDER-LESS ROAD. I AM UNABLE TO SEE WHAT IS TO BE DONE OTHER THAN GIVE UP THIS PART OF OUR BUSINESS - AT LEAST IN THE WINTER.  WE HAVE, IN FACT, GIVEN UP OUR CARRIER ACTIVITIES. WE ARE NOT REPLACING THE WRECKED TRUCK AND ALL FURTHER SALES WILL BE TRANSPORTED BY CONTRACTED CARRIERS. THIS IS NOT A PREVENTION MEASURE, AS THE CARRIERS ARE EXPOSED TO THE SAME RISKS. IT IS MERELY A COMMENT THAT WE NO LONGER FEEL DELIVERING FUEL TO GRANGEVILLE, IDAHO IN THE WINTER IS WORTH THE RISK DESPITE ALL SAFETY MEASURES.

column168: OUR TRANSPORT DRIVER NAVIGATED THE LEASE ROAD BACK TO THE LEASE LOCATION AND LOADED 166 BARRELS OF CRUDE OIL FROM THE RANKEN ENERGY JOHNSTON 1-13 OIL LEASE. UPON NAVIGATING HIS WAY BACK OUT OF THE 1 MILE LEASE ROAD HE FAILED TO NEGOTIATE A RIGHT TURN PRIOR TO NARROW STREAM CROSSING AND DROPPED THE PASSENGER SIDE REAR TRAILER TIRES OFF THE EMBARKMENT. THIS CAUSED AN IMMEDIATE LEAN OF A TOP HEAVY CRUDE OIL TANKER THUS ROLLING THE CRUDE OIL TRANSPORT (TRACTOR/TRAILER) ON ITS PASSENGER SIDE. ACCORDING TO THE DRIVER, THE VISIBILITY WAS LIMITED DUE TO FOGGY NIGHT TIME CONDITIONS AND HE WAS UNAWARE OF THE CROSSING EVEN THOUGH HE HAD ALREADY DROVE ACROSS IT COMING IN. WHEN THE TRANSPORT ROLLED ON TO ITS PASSENGER SIDE, THE TANKER TRAILER LANDED ON A 2" PIPE GATE POST THAT ANCHORS FENCING TO CATCH DEBRIS IN THE STREAM. SUBSEQUENTLY THE GATE POST PUNCTURED THE TANKER TRAILER SPILLING 146 BARRELS OF THE CRUDE OIL CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER INTO THE STEAM. THE DRIVER WAS ABLE TO EXIT THE TRANSPORT THROUGH KICKING OUT THE FRONT MANAGEMENT TEAM WHICH ALERTED OUR CONTRACT SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR. UPON ARRIVAL OF THE SPILL RESPONSE CONTRACTOR, BOOM WAS DEPLOYED IN 5 LOCATIONS STARTING 5 MILES DOWNSTREAM FROM THE ORIGIN OF THE SPILL AND SKIMMING OPERATIONS COMMENCED. A TOW TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO LIFT AND UPRIGHT TRANSPORT BACK ON THE LEASE ROAD.
column169: - THIS PARTICULAR LEASE HAS BEEN PLACED ON A DAYLIGHT HAUL ONLY LIST.  - COFFEYVILLE MANAGEMENT REACHED AN AGREEMENT WITH THE RANKEN ENERGY TO MAKE IMPROVEMENTS TO THE CROSSING/ROAD.  - THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED BASED ON THE INCIDENT OUTCOME AND PRIOR HISTORY.  - THE INVESTIGATION IS STILL ONGOING.

column168: ON 02/28/2019 AROUND 8:20 PM REPRESENTATIVE FROM CHEMTREC CONTACTED ME REGARDING A SPILL OF HAZMAT PRODUCT THAT WAS REPORTED TO THEM, BY OUR DRIVER JORGE MARIN. JORGE MARIN (PHONE # 804-931-5148) HAD THE TRACTOR-TRAILER COMBINATION (UNIT 160, FREIGHT LINER 2017, VIN #3AKJGLDR8HSHK5947 AND TRAILER 5381, WABASH 2019, WIN #1JJV532D8KL134482) PARKED AT LOVE'S TRAVEL STOPS & COUNTRY STORES IN OZARK, AL 36360, WHEN HE NOTICED A LARGE LEAK FROM THE TRAILER. CHEMTREC, FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE POLICE WERE IMMEDIATELY INFORMED SINCE THE PRODUCT HAULED WAS A HAZMAT MATERIAL, UN 1824 SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLUTION.AT ARRIVAL, THE FIRE DEPARTMENT SECURED THE AREA AND DID NOT LET ANYBODY NEAR THE TRUCK. THE ENVIRONMENTAL HAZMAT SERVICES, INC. WERE CALLED AND AUTHORIZED TO PERFORM THE CLEANUP AND THE MITIGATION OF THE SPILL. THEY INFORMED THERE WERE 3 TOTES DAMAGED, THAT LEAKED. TWO OF THEM WERE COMPLETELY EMPTY AND ONE HAD APPROXIMATELY 15-20 GALLONS LEFT IN IT. A REPRESENTATIVE FROM THE OZARK FIRE DEPARTMENT STATED THAT THE DAMAGED TOTES HAD HOLES PROBABLY PUNCHED BY THE PALLETS. DURING THE TRANSPORTATION THERE WAS NO HARD BREAKING EVENTS REPORTED, NOR ANY CRITICAL EVENTS, PLEASE SEE THE EVENTS REPORT BELOW (NO EVENTS FOR UNIT 160). PROBABLE REASON FOR THE DAMAGE OF THE TOTES IS THAT THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED. SINCE THERE WERE NO CRITICAL EVENTS REPORTED, WE BELIEVE THE TOTES WERE NOT LOADED AND SECURED PROPERLY AT THE SHIPPER. AS IT'S SEEN ON THE RATE CONFIRMATION ATTACHED BELOW AND AS PER OUR COMPANY POLICY, THE DRIVER IS NOT ALLOWED TO LOAD OR UNLOAD.
column169: WE BELIEVE THE INCIDENT OCCURRED DUE TO IMPROPER LOADING AND SECURING OF THE CARGO. OFTEN DRIVERS ARE NOT ALLOWED AT THE LOADING DOCK, ESPECIALLY WHEN HAZMAT PRODUCT IS INVOLVED, THEY CAN NOT SEE HOW THE CARGO IS SECURED. IN THIS PARTICULAR INCIDENT, THE LOAD HAD SHIFTED AND MOST LIKELY THE BROKEN PALLETS HAVE PUNCTURED THE TOTES. NO CRITICAL EVENTS OR HARD BRAKING EVENTS WERE DETECTED DURING THE TRANSPORTATION AS SEEN ON THE ATTACHED REPORT. OUR RECOMMENDATION IS FOR BETTER CONTROL REGARDING LOADING AND SECURING OF THE CARGO, IN PARTICULAR WHEN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL IS INVOLVED.

column168: THE ATLAS DRIVER ARRIVED AT THIS GAS STATION WITH A FULL LOAD OF REGULAR GASOLINE (87 OCTANE). IT WAS AT NIGHT AND WAS RAINING. HE IDENTIFIED THE WHITE COVER FOR REGULAR GASOLINE (DIFFERENT GRADES OF GAS HAVE DIFFERENT COLORED COVERS). HE TOOK A VEEDER-ROOT READING AND IT INDICATED THAT THERE WAS AROUND 2000 GALLONS ALREADY IN THE TANK, BUT HE DID NOT FOLLOW CORRECT PROCEDURE AND STICK THE TANK TO CONFIRM THE READING. SINCE HE WAS EXPECTING THIS TO BE AN 8000 GALLON TANK BY THE COVER COLOR, HE HOOKED UP THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE AND STARTED TO DROP ONE OF HIS 4000 GALLONS TANKS. SINCE IT WAS RAINING, THE DRIVER WENT AND SAT IN HIS TRUCK. THIS IS ALSO A BREACH OF COMPANY PROTOCOL AND PROCEDURE. OUR POLICY INDICATED THAT DRIVERS MUST STAY WITH THEIR LOADS WHILE DROPPING. AFTER A FEW MINUTES IN THE CAB, HE GOT OUT AND STOOD UNDER THE CANOPY, BUT HE DID NOT HAVE A SITE LINE TO THE DROP POINT. AFTER ABOUT 10 MINUTES HE WENT TO THE TANK AND NOTICED THAT THE TRUCK TANK WAS EMPTY. WHEN HE WENT TO DISCONNECT, HE SAW THAT E 85 WAS PAINTED ON THE CONCRETE NEAR THE TANK. E85 SHOULD HAVE A BROWN COVER. HE DID NOT SEE THIS WHEN HE SET UP HIS DROP. HE DID NOT SEE ANY GASOLINE IN THE BOWL AND HIS HOSE WAS STILL FIRMLY ATTACHED. OUR DRIVER WAS ALSO ABLE TO EMPTY HIS HOSE BACK INTO THE UNDERGROUND TANK (ABOUT 10 GALLONS), INDICATING THAT THE UST WAS NOT FULL. THIS IS WHERE THE ORIGINAL ESTIMATE OF 2000 GALLONS LOST CAME FROM THE E85 TANK IS A 4000 GALLON TANK, IT HAD ABOUT 2000 GALLONS IN IT WHEN HE STARTED TO DROP, THEREFORE 2000 GALLONS "LOST". OUR DRIVER ALSO IDENTIFIED A SMALL PINHOLE IN THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE WITH FUEL COMING OUT. WE BELIEVE THAT THIS VERY SMALL LEAK WAS THE CAUSE OF THE STRAINING IDENTIFIED IN THE PARKING LOT. WE DO NOT BELIEVE THAT 2000 GALLONS WERE LOST DOWN THE SEWER. FIRST, THE ODOR OF THAT MUCH GASOLINE WOULD BE OVERPOWERING THERE WAS NO ODOR. SECOND, THE PARKING LOT WOULD HAVE BEEN FLOODED WITH THAT MUCH GAS-IT WAS NOT. IN FACT, THERE WAS NO STANDING GASOLINE AT ALL.    THERE WAS NEVER ANY GASOLINE IDENTIFIED IN ANY OF THE BOOMS SET IN THE WATERWAYS AND NO VAPOR WAS EVER DETECTED USING THE PID DETECTORS. THIS IS CLEARLY STATED IN OUR REMEDIATION CONSULTANTS REPORT. THAT FACT THAT OUR DRIVER IDENTIFIED GASOLINE LEAKING FROM THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE INDICATED THAT THERE WAS FUEL IN THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE WHEN THERE SHOULD HAVE BEEN ONLY VAPOR.  WE BELIEVE A VERY SMALL AMOUNT, PERHAPS 1-2 GALLONS, WAS RELEASE IN THE PARKING LOT THROUGH THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE. THE REST OF THE FUEL WAS LIKELY FORCED THROUGH THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE BECAUSE OF THE PRESSURE IN THE TANK AND END UP IN THE OTHER UNDERGROUND TANKS. THERE IS ONLY ONE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE THAT IS CONNECTED TO ALL TANKS. THIS SET OF CIRCUMSTANCES IS RELATIVELY COMMON IN THE INDUSTRY.  IT MAKES NO SENSE THAT WE COULD HAVE LOST 2000 GALLONS DOWN THE STORM SEWER. THE TANK HAS A VALVE COVER ONTO WHICH OUR HOSE WAS STILL FIRMLY  ATTACHED, SO THE ONLY PLACE FOR THE GAS TO GO IS INTO THE VAP
column169: ALL OUR DRIVERS HAVE BEEN RE INSTRUCTED ABOUT THE IMPORTANCE OF FOLLOWING THE CORRECT FUEL DROP PROCEDURES, AND THIS PROCEDURE HAS BEEN REINFORCED IN OUR TRAINING. IN THIS CASE, WE BELIEVE THAT THE DRIVER WAS FEARFUL OF LOSING HIS JOB SO DID NOT IMMEDIATELY PROVIDE VITAL INFORMATION LIKE THE FUEL COMING OUT OF THE VAPOR RECOVERY LINE. OUR FIELD SUPERVISOR HAS BEEN AUDITING ALL OUR CUSTOMERS TO MAKE SURE THAT THE COVERS ARE ALL THE RIGHT COLOR. OFTEN IN THE WINTER, THE COVERS CAN BE RIPPED OFF BY SNOW PLOWS AND STATION OPERATORS WILL REPLACE THEM WITH WHATEVER THEY HAVE AVAILABLE. WE ALSO IDENTIFIED THAT THE VEEDER-ROOT SYSTEM AT THIS STATION WAS NOT WORKING PROPERLY AND GIVING FALSE READINGS. THIS, AS WELL, IS NOT UNCOMMON IN THE INDUSTRY, AND WHY WE INSIST THAT DRIVERS STICK THE TANKS AND NOT RELY EXCLUSIVELY ON THIS SYSTEM. WE BELIEVE THAT IT MIGHT BE A GOOD IDEA TO REQUIRE PREVENTIVE MAINTENANCE ON THESE SYSTEMS BY STATION OWNERS TO PREVENT SIMILAR ISSUES.
